ngus","Anconeus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe deep branch of the radial nerve, also known as the posterior interosseous nerve, pierces the \u003Cstrong\u003Esupinator\u003C/strong\u003E muscle. This allows it to enter the posterior compartment of the forearm where it innervates the extensor muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbductor pollicis longus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is innervated by the posterior interosseous nerve but is not pierced by it\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnconeus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is innervated by the radial nerve but not by its deep branch\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor carpi radialis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is innervated by the deep branch but is not pierced by it\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExtensor carpi radialis longus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is innervated by the radial nerve but not by its deep branch\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe deep branch of the radial nerve is crucial for the function of the extensor muscles in the forearm, enabling wrist and finger extension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The deep branch of the radial nerve, also known as the posterior interosseous nerve, passes through the supinator muscle.","The deep branch of the radial nerve innervates the extensor muscles in the forearm.","The deep branch of the radial nerve does not innervate the hand."],"references":["West, S. G. (2019). Anatomy and physiology of the musculoskeletal system. Rheumatology Secrets E-Book: Rheumatology Secrets E-Book, 17","Miniato MA, Anand P, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Shoulder and Upper Limb, Shoulder. 2023 Jul 24. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725618","Hutson, M., \u0026 Ward, A. (Eds.). 